Consumer-side transactions with PostgreSQL are crucial for ensuring exactly-once semantics (EOS) in a distributed order management system. This involves coordinating Kafka consumer offsets with database operations to ensure that both the message consumption and database updates are atomic. Below is a detailed guide on how to achieve this using Spring Boot, Apache Kafka, and PostgreSQL.

### Step 1: Configure Consumer Group

Ensure your consumers are configured to use transactional acknowledgment mode (`ack-mode: transaction`).

Example `application.yml`:
```yaml
spring:
  kafka:
    consumer:
      group-id: order-group
      auto-offset-reset: earliest
      enable-auto-commit: false # Disable auto-commit for manual control
      key-deserializer: org.apache.kafka.common.serialization.StringDeserializer
      value-deserializer: io.confluent.kafka.serializers.KafkaAvroDeserializer
      properties:
        schema.registry.url: http://localhost:8081
    listener:
      ack-mode: transaction
```

### Step 2: Configure Kafka Consumer Factory

Create a configuration class to set up the Kafka consumer factory with transactional acknowledgment.

```java
import org.apache.kafka.clients.consumer.ConsumerConfig;
import org.springframework.beans.factory.annotation.Value;
import org.springframework.context.annotation.Bean;
import org.springframework.context.annotation.Configuration;

@Configuration
public class KafkaConsumerConfig {

    @Value("${spring.kafka.bootstrap-servers}")
    private String bootstrapServers;

    @Bean
    public DefaultKafkaConsumerFactory<String, Object> consumerFactory() {
        Map<String, Object> configs = new HashMap<>();
        configs.put(ConsumerConfig.BOOTSTRAP_SERVERS_CONFIG, bootstrapServers);
        configs.put(ConsumerConfig.GROUP_ID_CONFIG, "order-group");
        configs.put(ConsumerConfig.KEY_DESERIALIZER_CLASS_CONFIG, StringDeserializer.class);
        configs.put(ConsumerConfig.VALUE_DESERIALIZER_CLASS_CONFIG, KafkaAvroDeserializer.class);
        configs.put("schema.registry.url", "http://localhost:8081");

        return new DefaultKafkaConsumerFactory<>(configs);
    }

    @Bean
    public ConcurrentKafkaListenerContainerFactory<String, Object> kafkaListenerContainerFactory() {
        ConcurrentKafkaListenerContainerFactory<String, Object> factory = new ConcurrentKafkaListenerContainerFactory<>();
        factory.setConsumerFactory(consumerFactory());
        factory.getContainerProperties().setAckMode(ContainerProperties.AckMode.TRANSACTIONAL);
        return factory;
    }
}
```

